<BaseLayout
  title="What is problem gambling?"
  description="Problem gambling is gambling that causes harm and is hard to control. It is a recognized health condition, not a lack of willpower."
>
  <header class="page-header">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="page-header__eyebrow">
        <a href="/understand-gambling">← Understand gambling</a>
      </p>
      <h1>What is problem gambling?</h1>
      <p class="page-header__lead">
        Problem gambling is gambling that harms a person's life — their money,
        relationships, work, or health — and is hard to control. It is a
        recognized health condition, not a moral failing or a lack of willpower.
      </p>
    </div>
  </header>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container prose">
      <h2>It happens on a spectrum</h2>
      <p>
        Gambling harm is not all-or-nothing. A person can be at low risk, at
        rising risk, or living with a serious gambling disorder. Help works at
        every point — you do not have to "hit bottom" to reach out. That is the
        idea behind a reset: re-evaluating your relationship with gambling at any
        time.
      </p>

      <h2>How professionals define it</h2>
      <p>
        Clinicians look for patterns over the past year, such as:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Thinking about gambling a lot, or planning the next time</li>
        <li>Needing to bet more money to feel the same excitement</li>
        <li>Feeling restless or irritable when trying to cut back</li>
        <li>Returning to win back losses ("chasing")</li>
        <li>Lying to hide how much you gamble</li>
        <li>Risking or losing relationships, school, or work</li>
        <li>Relying on others for money because of gambling</li>
        <li>Trying to stop or cut back without success</li>
        <li>Gambling to escape stress or low mood</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Recognizing some of these does not mean you have a disorder — only a
        trained professional can assess that. It does mean it may be worth talking
        to someone. The helpline can connect you, free of charge.
      </p>

      <h2>How common is it?</h2>
      <p>
        Most adults who gamble do not develop a problem. Still, roughly 2.5 million
        U.S. adults likely meet the criteria for a gambling disorder, and an
        estimated 5 to 8 million more show problematic gambling behavior. Risk is
        higher among adults 18–34. (National Council on Problem Gambling, NGAGE 3.0,
        2024.) These numbers shift over time, so they are best read as a trend, not
        a fixed fact.
      </p>

      <h2>The link to mental health</h2>
      <p>
        Gambling harm often occurs alongside stress, anxiety, depression, or
        substance use, and gambling disorder carries an elevated risk of suicide.
        If you or someone you know is in crisis, call or text
        <a href="tel:988">988</a>, the Suicide &amp; Crisis Lifeline, any time.
      </p>


      <div class="sources">
        <h2>Learn more</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><a href="https://www.ncpgambling.org/">National Council on Problem Gambling (NGAGE data)</a></li>
          <li><a href="https://www.samhsa.gov/mental-health/988">988 Suicide &amp; Crisis Lifeline (SAMHSA)</a></li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
